e, Normandie, Frankrig","France":"Frankrig"},"nl":{"0992–about 1060":"0992–circa 1060","0992–1060":"0992–1060","1002–1086":"1002–1086","1019–Male":"1019–Overleden","1022–1092":"1022–1092","0970–1030":"0970–1030","0967–1024":"0967–1024","about 1060":"circa 1060","1022":"1022","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1060":"1060","1092":"1092","1019":"1019","0992":"0992","0970":"0970","1024":"1024","1002":"1002","um 1019":"circa 1019","0967":"0967","about 1022":"circa 1022","Normandie, Frankreich":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Orne, Basse-Normandie, France":"Orne, Basse-Normandie, Frankrijk","Saye, Orne, Normandie, France":"Orne, Normandie, Frankrijk","France":"Frankrijk"},"en":{"0992–about 1060":"0992–about 1060","0992–1060":"0992–1060","1002–1086":"1002–1086","1019–Male":"1019–Deceased","1022–1092":"1022–1092","0970–1030":"0970–1030","0967–1024":"0967–1024","about 1060":"about 1060","1022":"1022","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1060":"1060","1092":"1092","1019":"1019","0992":"0992","0970":"0970","1024":"1024","1002":"1002","um 1019":"about 1019","0967":"0967","about 1022":"about 1022","Normandie, Frankreich":"Normandy, France","Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Orne, Basse-Normandie, France":"Orne, Lower Normandy, France","Saye, Orne, Normandie, France":"Orne, Normandy, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Arenel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Avenell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Avenell","meanings":["English: from the Old French personal name <i>Avenel</i>, a double diminutive of ancient Germanic <i>Avo</i>. The surname was later confused with   Averill  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Saye","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Sky  , influenced by the name of the island of <i>Skye</i> in the Hebrides, which is of Gaelic origin.  Compare  Ailsa  ,   lona  , and   Isla   for similar derivations."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert FitzPicot de Saye Arenel was born in 0992, in Orne, Lower Normandy, France, his father, Robert Fitz Picot de Saye Avenel, I, Lord of Aunay, was 23 and his mother, Adeloyse of Clun, was 25. He married Vicomtes Adeloya de Coimis in 1019, in Normandy, France. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1060, at the age of 69."},"et":{"0992–about 1060":"0992–umbes 1060","0992–1060":"0992–1060","1002–1086":"1002–1086","1019–Male":"1019–Surnud","1022–1092":"1022–10